<subSubSection pageId="12" pageNumber="289" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,1615,2037]" pageId="12" pageNumber="289">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,321,1724,1749]" pageId="12" pageNumber="289">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
This is the most distinctive species of genus 
<taxonomicName box="[843,963,1724,1749]" class="Insecta" family="Piophilidae" genus="Prochyliza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="289" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[843,963,1724,1749]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="289">Prochyliza</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The unusually elongated pedicel in both sexes (although much more elongated in males) (
<figureCitation box="[733,805,1759,1784]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1413,1435]" captionTargetBox="[254,1361,631,1387]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[224,1363,628,1392]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 4. Head of Prochyliza xanthostoma Walker, Prochyliza georgekaplani sp. nov. and Prochyliza nigrimana (Meigen). (A) P. xanthostoma, male head, lateral view; (B) P. xanthostoma, female head, lateral view; (C) P. georgekaplani, male head, lateral view; (D) P. nigrimana, female head, lateral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/224986/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="289">
Fig. 
<number box="[790,805,1760,1784]" pageId="12" pageNumber="289" value="4.0">4</number>
</figureCitation>
A, B) is an unmistakable diagnostic character for this species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="12" pageNumber="289" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,1615,2037]" pageId="12" pageNumber="289">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1831,1856]" pageId="12" pageNumber="289">Remarks.</emphasis>
As mentioned, 
<taxonomicName box="[502,676,1831,1856]" class="Insecta" family="Piophilidae" genus="Prochyliza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="289" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="xanthostoma">
<emphasis box="[502,676,1831,1856]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="289">P. xanthostoma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was the only species included in the originally monotypic genus 
<taxonomicName box="[151,271,1868,1893]" class="Insecta" family="Piophilidae" genus="Prochyliza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="289" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,271,1868,1893]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="289">Prochyliza</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Consequently, the original description of this genus referred to the distinctive characters of this species (
<bibRefCitation author="Walker" box="[158,308,1903,1928]" pageId="12" pageNumber="289" refString="Walker, F. (1849) List of the specimens of dipterous insects in the collection of the British Museum, Part IV. London, pp. 689 - 1172. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 20821" type="book chapter" year="1849">
Walker 
<number box="[248,308,1904,1928]" pageId="12" pageNumber="289" value="1849.0">1849</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). With the subsequent combination of other species under this genus made by 
<bibRefCitation author="McAlpine" box="[1193,1391,1903,1928]" pageId="12" pageNumber="289" refString="McAlpine, J. F. (1977) A revised classification of the Piophilidae, including ' Neottiophilidae' and ' Thyreophoridae' (Diptera: Schizophora). Memoirs of the Entomological Society of Canada, 103, 1 - 66. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.4039 / entm 109103 fv" type="journal article" year="1977">
McAlpine (
<number box="[1323,1383,1904,1928]" pageId="12" pageNumber="289" value="1977.0">1977</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
, his redescription of the genus 
<taxonomicName box="[448,568,1940,1965]" class="Insecta" family="Piophilidae" genus="Prochyliza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="289" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[448,568,1940,1965]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="289">Prochyliza</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
should be followed, as presented in the current paper.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="13" lastPageNumber="290" pageId="12" pageNumber="289" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,1615,2037]" lastBlockId="13.[151,1436,151,285]" lastPageId="13" lastPageNumber="290" pageId="12" pageNumber="289">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,295,1976,2001]" pageId="12" pageNumber="289">Biology.</emphasis>
The species breeds on carcasses (e.g. 
<bibRefCitation author="Bonduriansky" box="[735,1081,1976,2001]" pageId="12" pageNumber="289" refString="Bonduriansky, R. &amp; Brooks, R. J. (1999) Reproductive allocation and reproductive ecology of seven species of Diptera. Ecological Entomology, 24, 389 - 395. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 0014 - 3820.2005. tb 00901. x" type="journal article" year="1999">
Bonduriansky &amp; Brooks 
<number box="[1022,1081,1976,2000]" pageId="12" pageNumber="289" value="1999.0">1999</number>
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Tabor" box="[1094,1296,1976,2001]" pageId="12" pageNumber="289" refString="Tabor, K. L., Fell, R. D. &amp; Brewster, C. C. (2005) Insect fauna visiting carrion in Southwest Virginia. Forensic Science International, 150, 73 - 80. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1016 / j. forsciint. 2004.06.041" type="journal article" year="2005">
Tabor 
<emphasis box="[1168,1225,1976,2001]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="289">et al.</emphasis>
<number box="[1235,1296,1976,2001]" pageId="12" pageNumber="289" value="2005.0">2005</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Piophilidae" genus="Prochyliza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="289" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="xanthostoma">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="289">Prochyliza xanthostoma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has been used as a model organism for research on several topics like larval behaviour (
<bibRefCitation author="Bonduriansky" lastPageId="13" lastPageNumber="290" pageId="12" pageNumber="289" refString="Bonduriansky, R. (2002) Leaping behaviour and responses to moisture and sound in larvae of piophilid carrion flies. The Canadian Entomologist, 134, 647 - 656. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.4039 / ent 134647 - 5" type="journal article" year="2002">
Bonduriansky 
<number box="[151,211,152,176]" pageId="13" pageNumber="290" value="2002.0">2002</number>
</bibRefCitation>
), adult fitness (Bonduriansky 
<emphasis box="[590,657,151,176]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="290">et al.</emphasis>
<number box="[675,733,151,176]" pageId="13" pageNumber="290" value="2005.0">2005</number>
) or sexual selection (e.g. Bonduriansky &amp; Rowe 
<number box="[1372,1431,151,176]" pageId="13" pageNumber="290" value="2005.0">2005</number>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Bonduriansky" box="[151,376,188,213]" pageId="13" pageNumber="290" refString="Bonduriansky, R. (2006) Convergent evolution of sexual shape dimorphism in Diptera. Journal of Morphology, 267, 602 - 611. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1002 / jmor. 10426" type="journal article" year="2006">
Bonduriansky 
<number box="[315,376,188,213]" pageId="13" pageNumber="290" value="2006.0">2006</number>
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="13" pageNumber="290" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1436,151,285]" pageId="13" pageNumber="290">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,352,223,248]" pageId="13" pageNumber="290">Distribution.</emphasis>
Nearctic; originally recorded from Northeastern 
<collectingCountry box="[910,994,223,248]" name="Canada" pageId="13" pageNumber="290">Canada</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Walker" box="[1010,1160,223,248]" pageId="13" pageNumber="290" refString="Walker, F. (1849) List of the specimens of dipterous insects in the collection of the British Museum, Part IV. London, pp. 689 - 1172. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 20821" type="book chapter" year="1849">
Walker 
<number box="[1100,1160,224,248]" pageId="13" pageNumber="290" value="1849.0">1849</number>
</bibRefCitation>
), it is widely distributed throughout North 
<collectingCountry box="[353,449,260,285]" name="United States of America" pageId="13" pageNumber="290">America</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="McAlpine" box="[464,646,260,285]" pageId="13" pageNumber="290" refString="McAlpine, J. F. (1977) A revised classification of the Piophilidae, including ' Neottiophilidae' and ' Thyreophoridae' (Diptera: Schizophora). Memoirs of the Entomological Society of Canada, 103, 1 - 66. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.4039 / entm 109103 fv" type="journal article" year="1977">
McAlpine 
<number box="[586,646,260,284]" pageId="13" pageNumber="290" value="1977.0">1977</number>
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
